{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17638518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17638518"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:56:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17718"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17718","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17718"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10432"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72331"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10432"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17718"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57800"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4932"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"10184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24371"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24489"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72331"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EEpidermal wound healing is a complex process that restores skin integrity following injury.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the initial cellular response during re-epithelialisation of a skin wound?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cross-linking of collagen fibres","Formation of granulation tissue","Collagen deposition by fibroblasts","Keratinocyte migration from wound edges","Recruitment of inflammatory cells"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring re-epithelialisation, \u003Cstrong\u003Ekeratinocyte migration from wound edges\u003C/strong\u003E is the initial cellular response that begins within hours of injury. These cells detach from the basement membrane and migrate across the wound bed to restore the epithelial barrier.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECollagen deposition by fibroblasts\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during the later proliferative phase and continues through the remodelling phase.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of granulation tissue\u003C/strong\u003E develops later in wound healing and provides a scaffold for epithelial migration.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERecruitment of inflammatory cells\u003C/strong\u003E takes place during the inflammatory phase before re-epithelialisation begins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECross-linking of collagen fibres\u003C/strong\u003E happens during the final remodelling phase of wound healing, which can continue for months after injury.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKeratinocyte migration is followed by proliferation to restore the full thickness of the epidermis. This process is regulated by growth factors including epidermal growth factor and keratinocyte growth factor.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Epidermal wound healing occurs in three main phases: inflammation, proliferation, and remodelling.","Re-epithelialisation during wound healing involves keratinocyte migration and proliferation from the wound edges.","The proliferative phase of wound healing begins approximately 2-3 days after injury."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57800"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17718"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57800","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57800"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-21T07:36:58+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-21T07:37:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10432"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72331"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4932","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4932"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Skin and Associated Structures","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T12:54:20+10:30